snippet.textDisplay:
If you are a shill, can you get Disney to fund your fan-films? They would make a good feature length film!
Jokes aside, yeah, nah. You're not a shill. I came out of the movie happy. Sure the plot and story are contrived and mediocre at best, but I felt that is was because they were trying to make 3 films in one. Had it been put over two or three movies, it would not have been rushed and the contrivances would have been unnecessary.
I have my issues with it, but the film at least felt like an attempt to return to the Star Wars I knew before TFA, and tried to fix issues the fans had. We got Rey training and failing (although not much), we got backstory/development for Finn and Poe, we got some (albeit bad) story for Snoke, we got a backtrack from most of TLJ, we even got Reylo (sorta), and I finally got something I had been looking forward to since I first saw RotJ...Jedi Master Leia. These things should have come in TFA and TLJ, but sadly they did not. The point is that it was at least fun for me. The best of the saga? No, not by a mile. Best of the sequels? Yes for me.
Much like RotS, it suffers from, and had to fix, what came before.
And if you think it is too contrived or confused to be a good/fun movie, then try half of the stories fans got in Legends/EU. Some of the points are ripped straight from those stories. And some stories, such as all the Luke clones, are horrid.
Put bluntly, although the story is contrived, the fans were given things we wanted (or at least what I wanted) since TFA. The real issues are that Episode 9 had to retcon the issues in 7 and 8, there was no consistent story (or writer) for 3 movies, it was very rushed, and it was made as part of a sequel trilogy to a completed story. Ever since the sequel trilogy was announced, I feared it would fail because anything after RotJ will be compared to Eps IV-VI. Star Wars faces the same issue as Terminator and Alien...nothing compares to T2 or Aliens, and thus new films will always fall short.

I was 6 years old in 1977 when I first saw star wars, I didn't care what critics, or anyone else in that matter I just loved the movie. I could relate to Luke Skywalker and his struggle. My daughter looks up to Rey, a lonely scavenger girl becoming great, I would not take that away from her.
Took my family to see the rise of Skywalker and we all had a great time. That ment more to us than the critics or or the haters. That is what these movies are all about having a good time out with the family enjoying a movie with popcorn, Just like in 1977 with my Father.
